Product Segmentation Case Study

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

When you think of sneakers for a trip, the importance of good footwear cannot be discarded, and the obvious brands that come to mind are Adidas and Nike. Adidas vs Nike is a constant debate as the two giants in the apparel market, with a large market cap and market share, battle it out to come on top. As a newly hired Data Scientist in a market research company, you have been given the task of extracting insights from the data of men's and women's shoes, and grouping products together to identify similarities and differences between the product range of these renowned brands.

Objective¶

To perform an exploratory data analysis and cluster the products based on various factors using k-means algorithm and agglomerative clustering

Key Questions¶

  • Which variables are most important for clustering?
  • How each cluster is different from the others?
  • What are the business recommendations?

Data Description¶

The dataset consists of 3268 products from Nike and Adidas with features of information including their ratings, discount, sales price, listed price, product name, and the number of reviews.

  • Product Name: Name of the product
  • Product ID: ID of the product
  • Listing Price: Listed price of the product
  • Sale Price: Sale price of the product
  • Discount: Percentage of discount on the product
  • Brand: Brand of the product
  • Rating: Rating of the product
  • Reviews: Number of reviews for the product

Observations:¶

  • The median and mean of listing price are ~ 6000 and 7000, respectively. The spread of the listing price is fairly large, with its std being more than 2/3 of the mean. The minimum value of listing price is zero (!!), which doesn't make any sense. We'll take zero entries for listing price as missing values.
  • The sale price also has a large variation (std > 2/3 of the mean). Its median and mean are around 4600 and 6000, respectively, expectedly lower than the corresponding values of listing price. Note that the median of sale price is ~ 23% less than that of listing price, which is interestingly very close to the average discount. Note that medians are less influenced by missing values, and a better measure to evaluate the ratio of the two prices.
  • At least 25% of shoes are sold with no discount, and 25% of them get 50% discount or more. The mean and median discount are respectively ~ 28% and 40%.
  • Rating is a float-type value, varying from 0 to 5. The median and mean of this feature are 3.27 and 3.5, respectively, indicating that the customer satisfaction is average.
  • Some shoes have received no reviews and some has got as many as 223 reviews, but, on average, they've been reviewed about 42 times.
  • There are five unique brands, with Adidas Core/NEO being the most popular one, comprising about 35% of the data.

Treating the Missing Values¶

We'll proceed to fill in the missing values in the listing price column (zero values) using the available sale price and discount. In fact:

Listing Price = Sale Price * 1/(1 - Discount/100)

In [16]:
for i in range(df.shape[0]):
    if df.loc[i, 'Listing Price'] > 0:
        continue
    df.loc[i, 'Listing Price'] = df.loc[i, 'Sale Price']*(1/(1-0.01*df.loc[i, 'Discount']))

# Auxiliary function for annotating the bars in a countplot
def countplot_labeling(cntplt, data, perc = True, decimal = 1):
  ''' This function gets a countplot and the dataset that has generated
  the plot to produce the values corresponding to each bar (category).
  If perc = True, percentages will be shown.'''

  from math import isnan

  total = data.shape[0]  # total number of values in the dataset
  for p in cntplt.patches:
        height_val = float(p.get_height())
        if(isnan(height_val)):
          height_val = 0
        if(abs(height_val - round(height_val)) < 1e-6):
          height_val = int(height_val)  
        if perc == True:
          # percentage of each category
          label = "{:.1f}%".format(100*height_val/total)
        else:
          label = "{}".format(round(height_val,decimal))  # count of each category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width()/2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        if(height_val == 0):
          label = '0'

        # annotate the bar
        cntplt.annotate(label, (x, y), ha = "center", va = "center", size = 12, xytext = (0, 5), textcoords = "offset points")

Observations:¶

  • Unsurprisingly, listing and sales prices are heavily correlated, as listing price = discount * sale price.
  • Vendors reduce the percentage of discount for more expensive items, hence the negative correlation between the two.
  • More expensive items are sold less often and, thus have fewer reviews, which explains the negative correlation between the price and reviews.
  • Products with higher discounts are more likely to be sold and, as a result, to have higher numbers of reviews, hence the positive correlation between the percentage of discount and the number of reviews.

Generating K-Elbow Plot¶

Here, we vary the number of clusters (k) from 1 to 10 and generate the mean distortions plot w.r.t. k.

In [36]:
# Range of k values
k_range = np.arange(1, 11)
mean_distorions = np.zeros(len(k_range))
# Looping over all k values
for k in k_range:
    kmeans_model = KMeans(n_clusters = k, random_state = 1)
    segments_pred = kmeans_model.fit_predict(df_clust_scaled)
    mean_distorions[k-1] = sum(np.min(np.square(cdist(df_clust_scaled, kmeans_model.cluster_centers_, 'Euclidean')),
                                      axis = 1))/df_clust_scaled.shape[0]
# Plotting mean distrotion for all values of k
plt.figure(figsize = (8, 5));
plt.plot(k_range, mean_distorions, color = 'blue', marker = 'o');
plt.xticks(ticks = k_range);
plt.xlim(k_range[0]-0.25, k_range[-1]+0.25);
plt.xlabel('k');
plt.ylabel('Mean Distortion');
plt.title('Mean Distortion Score');
In [37]:
# Using Python's method
plt.figure(figsize = (8, 5));
visualizer = KElbowVisualizer(estimator = KMeans(random_state = 1), k = k_range, timings = False)
visualizer.fit(df_clust_scaled)        
plt.xticks(ticks = k_range);
plt.xlim(k_range[0]-0.25, k_range[-1]+0.25);
visualizer.show();

Observations:¶

  • Note that both elbow plots represent the same thing, except the scores of the first plot are averaged over the entire clusters.
  • Above elbow plots don't reveal a clear-cut optimal k. The plot generated by Yellowbrick's method declares k = 3 as the optimal value, but k = 4 or 5 also don't look too different. Therefore, we will determine the optimal value of k among these candidates via silhouette score.

Comparing Silhouette Scores¶

Since the results of the K-Elbow plot weren't very definitive, we calculate the silhouette score for each k value, as well.

In [38]:
# Calculating the mean silhouette score for all values of k

# Array of silhouette scores for all values of k
sil_scores = np.zeros(len(k_range)-1);

# Looping over all k values
for k in k_range[1:]:
    kmeans_model = KMeans(n_clusters = k, random_state = 1)
    segments_pred = kmeans_model.fit_predict(df_clust_scaled)
    sil_scores[k-2] = silhouette_score(df_clust_scaled, kmeans_model.labels_)

# Plotting the variation of silhouetter score with k
plt.figure(figsize = (8, 5));
plt.plot(k_range[1:], sil_scores, color = 'blue', marker = 'o');
plt.xlabel('k');
plt.ylabel('Silhouette Score');
plt.title('Average Silhouette Score vs. k');

Making Predictions with the Best k Value¶

Building the model using the value of k that leads to the best compromise between compression and accuracy.

In [42]:
# Building the final model
final_kmeans_model = KMeans(n_clusters = 4, random_state = 1);
# Deciding the cluster of each data point using the final model
segments_pred = final_kmeans_model.fit_predict(df_clust_scaled)

# Adding the determined clusters to the original and the scaled datasets
df_kmeans = df.copy()
df_kmeans_scaled = df_clust_scaled.copy()
df_kmeans['Cluster'] = segments_pred
df_kmeans_scaled['Cluster'] = segments_pred

  • Cluster 1 is made up of the most affordable shoes, which are sold more oftern and, as a result, have higher number of reviews.
  • Unsurprisingly, cluster 1 which is supposed to attract lower-income customers gets the highest percentage of discount.
  • The listing prices of cluster 1 and 3 are very close, but since the former gets more discounts, its sale price is noticeably lower.
  • Cluster 2 has the lowest count, as most likely isn't produced and sold very often, usually has very few reviews and a much lower rating than the other clusters.

Hierarchical Clustering¶

Impact of Distance Metric and Linkage Method¶

Here, we determine which combination of distance (affinity) metric and linkage method result in the highest cophenetic correlation.

In [76]:
# Listing the distance metrics and linkage methods
dist_metrics = ['cityblock', 'euclidean', 'chebyshev', 'mahalanobis']
link_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average']

# cophenetic correlation matrix of all combinations
c = np.zeros((len(dist_metrics), len(link_methods)))

# Looping over all metrics and methods
for i, dist_metric in enumerate(dist_metrics):
    for j, link_method in enumerate(link_methods):
        # Performing agglemorative clustering for the given distance metric and linkage method
        Z = linkage(df_clust_scaled, metric = dist_metric, method = link_method)
        # Computing the cophenetic correlation
        c[i][j], coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(df_clust_scaled))

print('Maximum cophenetic correlation attained is {}.'.format(round(np.max(c), 3)))
print('Linkage Method leading to maximum cophenetic correlation:', 
      dist_metrics[np.unravel_index(np.argmax(c), c.shape)[0]])
print('Linkage Method leading to maximum cophenetic correlation:', 
      link_methods[np.unravel_index(np.argmax(c), c.shape)[1]])

Maximum cophenetic correlation attained is 0.779.
Linkage Method leading to maximum cophenetic correlation: cityblock
Linkage Method leading to maximum cophenetic correlation: average

Observations:¶

  • Among provided distance metrics and linkage methods the combination of city block and average result in the highest cophenetic correlation. However, we also need to see how the combination of euclidean distance with centroid and Ward's methods work before making the final decision.
  • Note that centroid and Ward's linkage methods can't be combined by any other metric besides Euclidean, and that's why we didn't include them in the loop.
In [80]:
# List of linkage methods only compatible with Euclidean
link_methods = ['centroid', 'ward']

for link_method in link_methods:
    # Performing agglemorative clustering for the Euclidean distance metric and the given linkage method
    Z = linkage(df_clust_scaled, metric = 'euclidean', method = link_method)    
    # Computing the cophenetic correlation
    cc, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(df_clust_scaled))
    print('For Euclidean distance metric and {} linkage method, the cophenetic correlation is {}.'
          .format(link_method, round(cc, 3)))
    del Z, coph_dists

For Euclidean distance metric and centroid linkage method, the cophenetic correlation is 0.746.
For Euclidean distance metric and ward linkage method, the cophenetic correlation is 0.52.

Observations:¶

None of the Ward's or centroid method (combined with Euclidean distance) can improve the result of city block distance metric and average linkage method.

Selecting the Optimal Number of Clusters¶

Here, we explore the dendrogram for the pair of affinity and linkage leading to the highest cophenetic correlation, in order to select the optimal number of threshold or the cutting threshold for distances between the clusters.

In [84]:
# Dendogram of with the default hyperparameters of agglomerative clustering
Z = linkage(df_clust_scaled, metric = 'euclidean', method = 'ward')    
plt.figure(figsize = (13, 6));
dendrogram(Z);
plt.title('Dendrogram with Metric = Euclidean and Linkage Method = Ward');
plt.xticks([]);
In [85]:
# Dendogram of with the hyperparameters resulting in the highest cc
Z = linkage(df_clust_scaled, metric = 'cityblock', method = 'average')    
plt.figure(figsize = (13, 6));
dendrogram(Z);
plt.title('Dendrogram with Metric = City Block and Linkage Method = Average');
plt.xticks([]);
In [105]:
# Dendogram of with the hyperparameters resulting in the second highest cc
Z = linkage(df_clust_scaled, metric = 'euclidean', method = 'average')    
plt.figure(figsize = (13, 6));
dendrogram(Z);
plt.title('Dendrogram with Metric = Euclidean and Linkage Method = Average');
plt.xticks([]);

Observations:¶

  • However the default hyperparameters of the agglomerative clustering method resulted in a fairly low cophenetic correlation, but it's been able to separate data points into far more distinct clusters than the pairs of distance metrics and linkage methods leading to the top two highest cophenetic correlations. Therefore, we'll choose to proceed with the default hyperparameters of the agglomerative clustering method while building the final method.
  • Seemingly, the Ward's method is much more successful than other linkage methods in separating data points into distinguishable clusters.
  • The optimal number of clusters appears to be 3.

Building the Final Model¶

In [106]:
# Building the final hierarchical clustering model using 
# distance metric = Euclidean & linkage method = ward's
final_hc_model = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters = 3)
# Determining the cluster of each data point using the built model
clusters_pred = final_hc_model.fit_predict(df_clust_scaled)

# Adding the determined clusters to the original and the scaled datasets
df_hc = df.copy()
df_hc_scaled = df_clust_scaled.copy()
df_hc['Cluster'] = clusters_pred
df_hc_scaled['Cluster'] = clusters_pred

Displaying the boxplot distribution of each numerical feature w.r.t. the clusters for the original data

# Listing the numerical features

Observations:¶

  • The most expensive items are placed in cluster 2, which is apparently the equivalent of cluster 0 of k-means algorithm. Average discount of this cluster is about 30%.
  • The most affordable items are put in cluster 1. This cluster, which is analogous to cluster 1 of k-means algorithm, also has the highest discounts.
  • The listing price of cluster 2 is somewhat higer than cluster 1. The gap between the sale prices of the two widens, as cluster 2 has mean discount of close to zero.
  • Cluster 0 has the lowest ratings and cluster 2 has the highest ratings, but, overall, there isn't much difference between the ratings of all clusters. The gap in the number of reviews among the clusters is even smaller.
  • As can be noted, k-means clustering has proven more skilled in differentiating between the segments, and leveraging all attributes to produce distinct clusters. For instance, agglemorative clustering has barely utilized rating and reviews in its segmentation.
